{
  "text": "The dead-time problem has already been investigated by the industry [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] and various solutions have been proposed. In most cases the compensation techniques are based on an average value theory, the lost volt-seconds are averaged over an entire period and added to the commanded value. A pulse-based compensation method has been proposed in [CITATION_3] , where the compensation is realized for each pulse. The compensation voltages in [CITATION_4] are calculated by using dead-time, switching period, current command and dc-link voltage. Regardless of the method used, all dead-time compensation techniques are based on polarity of the current. This is especially true around the zero-crossing where an accurate measurement is needed to correctly compensate for the dead-time. In [CITATION_5] an online dead-time compensation technique is presented, acquiring the additional computation burden to determine the phase angle of currents.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "114624165",
    "[CITATION_2]": "17770514",
